  "output": "Both cursor-follow rAF loops clean up correctly, and VideoLightbox's timer queue has a matching `clearTimers()`. Here's the actual analysis, based on what's real in this codebase.\n\n## 1. N+1 query patterns — not applicable\n\nThis is a static, client-only React/Vite site. No database, no REST/GraphQL loop-fetching — the only network call is a single Formspree POST in `ContactModal.tsx`. There's nothing to N+1 here; skipping this section rather than inventing a finding.\n\n## 2. Unnecessary re-renders / render-path cost\n\n**Real issue — `Navbar.tsx`'s scroll handler does layout-forcing DOM work on every scroll event, unthrottled:**\n\n```js\nwindow.addEventListener('scroll', update, { passive: true })\n```\n\n`update()` calls `sampleBg()`, which does `document.elementFromPoint()` + walks up the DOM calling `getComputedStyle()` on every ancestor until it finds an opaque background. `elementFromPoint`/`getComputedStyle` both force a synchronous style/layout pass. Lenis fires scroll events at a high rate — this runs the full DOM walk every one of those frames.\n\n```js\n// Navbar.tsx\nuseEffect(() => {\n  let ticking = false\n  function update() {\n    if (isPhone) return\n    // ...existing body...\n  }\n  const onScroll = () => {\n    if (ticking) return\n    ticking = true\n    requestAnimationFrame(() => { update(); ticking = false })\n  }\n  window.addEventListener('scroll', onScroll, { passive: true })\n  onScroll()\n  return () => window.removeEventListener('scroll', onScroll)\n}, [])\n```\n\nrAF-coalescing caps the DOM-walk cost to once per paint instead of once per scroll tick — same visual result, far fewer forced layouts.\n\n**Minor — `AboutSection.tsx` / `WorkSection.tsx` rebuild their translated arrays every render:**\n\n```js\nconst services = serviceKeys.map((key) => ({ n: key, title: t(...), body: t(...) }))\n```\n\nThis reruns (and calls `t()` 8–12 times) on *every* re-render, including the ones caused by unrelated local state (`hovered`, `watchHover`). With 3–4 items this costs nothing measurable — flagging it, not fixing it. If `services`/`projects` ever grow past a handful of entries or `t()` stops being a cheap dictionary lookup, wrap in `useMemo(() => ..., [t])`.\n\n## 3. Caching opportunities\n\n**`ContactSection.tsx` recomputes an `Intl.DateTimeFormat` on every render:**\n\n```js\nconst vilniusOffset = new Intl.DateTimeFormat('en-US', {...}).formatToParts(new Date())...\n```\n\nThis is in the render body, not memoized, so it reconstructs the formatter and reformats on every re-render — including the two `gsap.set(autoAlpha)` visibility toggles this component's own `ScrollTrigger` fires. It only needs to change if the client is open across a DST boundary (irrelevant mid-session):\n\n```js\nconst vilniusOffset = useMemo(() => (\n  new Intl.DateTimeFormat('en-US', { timeZone: 'Europe/Vilnius', timeZoneName: 'shortOffset' })\n    .formatToParts(new Date())\n    .find((p) => p.type === 'timeZoneName')?.value ?? 'GMT+2'\n), [])\n```\n\nNo other real caching gaps — this is a marketing site with static assets, no data-fetch layer to memoize against.\n\n## 4. Memory leaks\n\nChecked every `useEffect`/rAF/timer pair by hand — all are symmetric:\n- `useLenis`: `gsap.ticker.remove` + `lenis.destroy()` on unmount ✓\n- `CursorScroll`, `WorkSection`'s watch-cursor loop: both `cancelAnimationFrame` on cleanup ✓ (verified `WorkSection.tsx:116`)\n- `VideoLightbox`: timers pushed via `schedule()` are all drained through `clearTimers()` (verified `VideoLightbox.tsx:148-154`) ✓\n- `AboutSection`: `gsap.context().revert()` cleans its tweens/ScrollTriggers ✓\n- `Navbar`, `ContactModal`, `WorkSection`: listeners added/removed symmetrically ✓\n\nNo leaks found. Not flagging anything here — inventing one would be worse than reporting none.\n\n## 5. Redundant computation — the one real duplication\n\nThe exact same \"lerp cursor toward target on rAF\" pattern (`pos += (target - pos) * 0.03`) is hand-written **three times**: `CursorScroll.tsx`, `WorkSection.tsx` (watch-hint), `VideoLightbox.tsx` (custom cursor). Same constant (`0.03`), same shape, three copies.\n\n```ts\n// src/cinematic/useCursorFollow.ts\nimport { useEffect, useRef, type RefObject } from 'react'\n\nexport function useCursorFollow(elRef: RefObject<HTMLElement>, ease = 0.03) {\n  const target = useRef({ x: 0, y: 0 })\n  const pos = useRef({ x: 0, y: 0 })\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    let raf: number\n    const tick = () => {\n      pos.current.x += (target.current.x - pos.current.x) * ease\n      pos.current.y += (target.current.y - pos.current.y) * ease\n      if (elRef.current) {\n        elRef.current.style.transform =\n          `translate3d(${pos.current.x}px,${pos.current.y}px,0) translate(-50%,-50%)`\n      }\n      raf = requestAnimationFrame(tick)\n    }\n    raf = requestAnimationFrame(tick)\n    return () => cancelAnimationFrame(raf)\n  }, [elRef, ease])\n\n  return target // caller writes target.current = {x, y} on pointer move\n}\n```\n\n→ skipped applying this myself: it touches three files' rAF wiring and I'd rather you confirm the extraction is worth the diff before I move working animation code around. Say the word and I'll wire all three call sites to it.\n\n---\n\n**Bottom line:** this codebase is already lean — no DB, no unmemoized data layer, no leaked effects. The one change worth actually making is the Navbar scroll throttle (#2); it's the only thing here that can visibly jank on scroll. The rest are penny-level, skip unless profiling says otherwise.\n",
